Hey guys, so I will be looking to create a new pair liquidity pool. But I'm trying to understand how pool creators actually make money? Can anyone help with this?
Do we get a % like everyone else per transaction? As part of the fee

Hi there, you can check resources here: 
v2: https://docs.uniswap.org/protocol/V2/concepts/core-concepts/pools
v3: https://docs.uniswap.org/protocol/concepts/V3-overview/concentrated-liquidity
So I can't see how actual liquidity owners make money? Or is an owner treated as a normal liquidity provider?
Yes, as liquidity provider. LPs earn from swap fees which is distributed pro-rata. But can also be subject to impermanent loss: https://academy.binance.com/en/articles/impermanent-loss-explained

it wasnt like that last week, just seen this message today
normally it allows to just swap
I has been like that since. But if you are referring to the "Allow uniswap protocol". It is because you are trying to spend a token that is not ETH

The first time you do a swap or liquidity add from a particular token, you have to approve it. This makes it so you can swap that token on Uniswap. From then on, you can swap from that token with only one step. However, the first time requires the approval and *then* the swap. You are charged an Ethereum transaction fee for the approval. Check #new-user-guide for more info https://discord.com/channels/597638925346930701/805509196031983637/805843069211508748

Actually Hayden gave a really good reason for using flashswaps instead of flashloans. If you want to take 3x eth leverage say, using MakerDao (put eth collateral, get dai, swap for eth, put more eth collateral, get dai, swap for more eth, etc.) then you would pay a lot of gas, so you can use flashswaps instead. Flashloans wouldn't work in this case because you would say borrow all the eth you need, deposit in maker-vault, and then have to use uniswap anyways to swap the dai for eth to repay the flashloan, so you would still incur the 0.3% uniswap fees, on TOP of the 0.09% flashloan fees.

I'm new to DeFi. I wanted to share my experience with providing liquidity to a trading pair in Uniswap. Hopefully another newcomer will see this and avoid the mistakes that I made. And hopefully some more seasoned DeFi experts can chime in on the numerous things I did wrong and give advice on how to do it right.

I wanted to get my feet wet by playing with $100 of ETH from my coinbase wallet so I went to Uniswap and swapped $50 ETH for $50 LOOK ---> ~$50 gas fee
I then set up a ETH/LOOK trading pair for approval ---> ~$20 gas fee
Then I added my ETH/LOOK to the liquidity pool with +-10% range ---> ~$120 gas fee
After about 5 hours I made ~$3 (Not bad. At that rate I would recoup my money after 12 days and afford to claim after another 10 days)

The problem: The pair fell out of range because LOOK went up 10% and ETH went slightly down

I now have <$100 of liquidity and ~$3 of earnings to claim but the gas fee is ~$115-$155. Needless to say, I AM NOT CLAIMING IT....

All in all my "getting my feet wet" experiment cost me ~$290

I‚Äôm having some trouble in trying to swap my coin, but the gas fee is high
You can monitor gas fees here https://etherscan.io/gastracker

Also note that you can edit your gas fees to a lower number (at least on MetaMask).  The transaction will just be sitting in the pending state until the gas price drops down to whatever fee you set.  This is nice if you need to make a transaction that isn't time sensitive and you don't want to have to set your alarm clock for the middle of the night when the fees are low.  When editing your gas fee just a couple points to know.

Gas Limit - NEVER change the "gas limit" that is automatically there.  This is the amount of gas that is required for a transaction....something like a simple swap will require less gas than minting an NFT.

Max priority fee - this goes to the miner of the block that validates your transaction.  Technically if there are 2 transactions with the same gas amount and different priority fees they will take the higher priority fee.  Typically I might set mine to 3 or 4 GWEI.  (it is only a couple cents difference)

Max Fee - this is where all the change really happens.  You can change this number to whatever amount of gas you want to pay.  But a couple things to keep in mind.  The transaction will be "stuck" in pending until the gas price lowers to whatever number you set.  If you set it too low this could mean your transaction is stuck indefinitely.  You also won't be able to make another transaction on the Ethereum Mainnet until the current pending one clears....(although you can always up your gas price later if you need to speed it up).  So back to what number to set your gas price...  Use the Etherscan Gas Tracker linked above and see click the "historical gas oracle price" tab part way down.  It will show you a graph with the max, average and low gas price for each day in the last 7 days.  Most days it looks like it hit the 50s for the last week...which is much better than the current 280  I have had pretty good luck with setting the price between 40 and 60 if I am willing to wait for a few days.

hello i got a question , where do the earning of liquidity pool go? for example i put a liquidity 1 uni/eth.  where do the 0.03 pct transaction earnings go? in my liquidity pool? if i unstake it thats the time i get the rewards?

Hi there, fees are distributed pro-rata to all liquidity providers on that pool. For v2, the fees are auto-compounded. While on v3 it's not--you can claim fees without removing your liquidity or remove your liquidity including your fees at the same time.
